Pleasure on the contrary, accord- ing to most Stoics, is not to be reckoned among the primary objects of natural impulse3 and I very strongly agree with them, for sear lest many immoral consequences would follow if we held that nature has placed pleasure among the earliest objects of desire. But the fact of our affection for the objects first adopted at nature’s prompting seems to require no further proof than this, that there is no one who, given the choice, would not prefer to have all the parts of his body sound and whole, rather than maimed or distorted although equally serviceable.

“Agziin, acts of cognition (which we may term comprehensions or perceptions, or, if these words are distasteful or obscure, kalalspseis), — these we con- sider meet to be adopted for their own sake, because the}v possess an element that so to speak embraces and contains the truth. This can be seen in the case of children, whom we may observe to take pleasure in finding something out for themselves by the use of reason, even though they gain nothing by it. The sciences also, we consider, are things to be chosen for their own sake, partly because there is in them something worthy of choice, partly because they consist of acts of cognition and contain an clement of fact established by methodical reasoning. The mental assent to what is false, as the Stoics believe, is more repugnant to us than all the other things that are contrary to nature.
